<div id="review_1924270498" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1924270498" />
    <a title="Karla" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2846441-karla"><img alt="Karla" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1537371209p2/2846441.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1924270498?book_show_action=true">Feb 25, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karla" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karla" href="/user/show/2846441-karla">Karla</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2846441-karla?shelf=ebook">ebook</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1924270498" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14227527670144937526">The premise was catchy, but I had no idea it would basically turn into an endless episode of <i>Dystopian God Talk</i> <u>and</u> be mired in some pretty godawful pedantic prose that reminded me of <i>Twilight</i> at its worst, such as:<br/><br/><i>I waited until I heard Cory go to her room and shut the door. Then I got up, shut my door, moved my lamp so the light wouldn&apos;t show under the door, then turned it on and opened my grandmother&apos;s Bible.</i><br/><br/>Good gravy. D: <br/><br/>Cue the epic &quot;Bella puts a CD in a player&quot; scene that, somehow, has be</span>
  <span id="freeText14227527670144937526" style="display:none">The premise was catchy, but I had no idea it would basically turn into an endless episode of <i>Dystopian God Talk</i> <u>and</u> be mired in some pretty godawful pedantic prose that reminded me of <i>Twilight</i> at its worst, such as:<br /><br /><i>I waited until I heard Cory go to her room and shut the door. Then I got up, shut my door, moved my lamp so the light wouldn't show under the door, then turned it on and opened my grandmother's Bible.</i><br /><br />Good gravy. D: <br /><br />Cue the epic "Bella puts a CD in a player" scene that, somehow, has been burned into my memory forever due to its bland step-by-step nature.<br /><br />OK, but maybe it's unfair to ding a book on such slim grounds. After all, not every sentence can be a pearl. And I only managed to get halfway before the aggravation with style and execution was making it deeply unpleasant to pick it back up. So <i>maybe</i> there was a nuclear blast of gold in the last half I missed.<br /><br />However, for what I did read, the world itself didn't ring true, even for a bleak future of dystopian chaos. Based on the descriptions given and implied by some of the characters, California has basically become an entire squalid inner city with little enclaves trying to become gated communities and protect themselves from the murderous, drug-addled hordes outside. Oregon and Washington are somewhat better, with Canada being the brass ring for plucky refugees. Regions east (such as the Deep South) are beset with plague and societal breakdown.<br /><br />Yet the main character and her friend discuss college as a valid means of escaping the crappy life that California offers. Would book-learning help in a society such as this? What are the colleges like in this 2025 hellscape of limited technology and meager resources? Have their focuses changed in keeping with the changing society and its needs? Does not compute.<br /><br />The blurbs that head each chapter - extracts from the MC's Enlightened survivalist faith she concocts in her spare time - didn't illuminate much, being cryptic, pseudo-profound fortune cookies of woo-woo.<br /><br />I'd rather more effort and creativity had been spent on the world-building than New Christianity poetry slams.<br /><br />And what about her "hyperempathy" gift/curse? That thing only gets trotted out when a point needs to be made. It wasn't deployed consistently.<br /><br />In all, very uneven and the gaping holes of continuity and logic were all the more glaring because there was little to distract from them. Certainly not the writing which, despite not being categorized as YA since it predates the rise of that genre, had a YA feel in its simplicity. There's spare, and then there's leaden. This was the latter.<br /><br />I've been wanting to read <i>Kindred</i> forever, but based on critical reviews of this one, the writing is just Butler's thing and you either love it or hate it (or suffer through it for the Theme). So I doubt I'll be putting more Butler on my TBR anytime soon.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14227527670144937526" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


